{
  "doc_id": "11449",
  "text": "Uterine leiomyomas are among the most common tumors in women, affecting 20% to 50% of reproductive women, which can cause dysmenorrhea, abnormal uterine bleeding, menorrhagia,and infertility. [CITATION_1] Uterine leiomyomas are generally considered as hormonal-dependent tumors; progesterone and estrogen are essential for growth and maintenance of leiomyomas. [CITATION_2] Except invasive surgical procedure, medical therapies are more widely used for symptomatic patients, including gonadotropin-releasing hormone agonists (GnRHa) and progesterone modulators. [CITATION_3] Mifepristone (formerly known as RU-486), is an antiprogesterone drug that is effective in treatment of uterine leiomyomas, resulting in decreased leiomyomas size and relieved symptoms. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Long-term administration of low-dose (5 or 10 mg daily for 1 year, [CITATION_6] 2.5 mg daily for 6 months, [CITATION_7] etc) mifepristone results in leiomyomas shrinkage and amelioration of symptoms. However, Eisinger et al [CITATION_8] reported that uterine leiomyoma regrowth occurs slowly after the cessation of mifepristone treatment, 5.7 months follow-up after cessation of mifepristone, almost 20% baseline of uterine volume increased compared with 12 months mifepristone treatment end. When GnRHa (another hormone replacement drug for uterine leiomyomas) treatment is stopped, uterine leiomyomas can also re-grow rapidly, and the uterine volume can reach or even exceed the baseline volume. [CITATION_9] It is a challenge for medical therapy of uterine leiomyomas.",
  "correct_citation": {
